AGI - Our personality alters the expression of our genes>. This is demonstrated by an international study conducted by the University of Granada >(Spain) using artificial intelligence and published in the magazine Molecular Psychiatry (Nature). The multi-disciplinary study was conducted by researchers at the Andalusian Interuniversity Institute of Data Science and Computational Intelligence (DaSCI), the Department of Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence of UGR and the Institute of Biohealth Research of Granada (ibs.GRANADA).
The study was carried out in collaboration with Professor Robert Cloninger (Washington University of St. Louis), researchers at Baylor College of Medicine (Texas, USA) and Young Finns Study (Finland). The international research group (composed of specialists in genetics, medicine, psychology and computer science) used the data of the Young Finns Study, a large study conducted on the general population of Finland > for more than four decades during which relevant information on the health of participants, physical condition and lifestyle was collected. In addition, participants were subjected to in-depth assessments of the personality > which concerned both temperament (inhabitants and emotional responsiveness) and character (objectives and conscious values).
&nbsp;
The results showed that some visions of life favour a healthy, fulfilling and long life, while others lead to a stressful, unhealthy and short life. The study analysed the regulation of genetic expression in these individuals, taking into account three levels of self-awareness measured through the combination of their temperament and character profiles. These levels have been defined as "unregulated" - individuals dominated by irrational emotions and habits associated with their traditions and obedience to authority, "organized" - self-sufficient individuals > can deliberately adjust their habits and cooperate with others for mutual advantage and, finally, "creative" - self-transcendent individuals > that adapt their habits to live in harmony with others, with the universe also if they require occasional sacrifices.
&nbsp;
As the researcher of the UGR explains and co-author of the study Coral del Val: "In our research we have made two key discoveries on the expression and organization of genes according to the personality profiles of these individuals. First, we discovered a network of 4,000 genes grouped into multiple modules expressed in specific regions of the brain. Some of these genes had already been linked in studies prior to the heredity of human personality. Secondly, we discovered that the modules formed a functional interaction network capable of orchestrating changes in genetic expression to adapt to the different internal and external conditions. The modules activated and deactivated in a flexible way, facilitating adaptation to the daily challenges that we all face and choreographer our development."
Researchers have shown that changes in the patterns of interaction between these modules were orchestrated by two subnets. A network regulates emotional reactivity > (anxiety, fear, etc.), while the other regulates what a person perceives as significant > (e.g. the production of concepts and language). "The most remarkable thing is the fact that the networks of emotions and meaning are coordinated by a control center composed of six genes", says Elisa Dìaz de la Guardia-Bolìvar, the other co-author of the study.
&nbsp;
"It is particularly interesting that we have discovered that the six genes of the control center are highly preserved during evolution, from unicellular organisms to modern human beings. This discovery confirms their beneficial role in adjusting the functioning of all forms of life on Earth," he adds. Identifying these genetic networks and the control center that regulates gene expression in humans has practical value because it shows how people can improve the quality of their health, happiness and general quality of everyday life, despite the challenges and stress we all face.
Igor Zwir of the UGR explains: "In previous research, we found significant differences in the well-being of people in the three groups of personalities, depending on their level of self-awareness. Specifically, those with greater self-awareness (the creative group) have brought greater well-being than organized and unregulated groups. We have now shown that these levels of self-awareness are also strongly associated with the regulation of gene expression in the same organized (creative) order. This suggests that a person can improve their health and well-being by cultivating a more self-transcendent and creative vision of life." &nbsp;

